questions.explanationMd:
`fetch()` only rejects when the request **cannot be made** at all:
- Network failure / offline
- DNS resolution failure
- CORS block
- Request aborted

HTTP error statuses (4xx, 5xx) are **not** rejections — the promise resolves normally. You must check:

```js
const res = await fetch(url);
if (!res.ok) {
  throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
}
```

In Express, a middleware **must** either:
1. Call `next()` to pass control to the next middleware
2. Send a response (`res.send()`, `res.json()`, `res.end()`, etc.)

If neither happens, the request **hangs**. The client will eventually time out.

```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log('Request received');
  // ⚠️ Forgot to call next() or send a response!
  // The request will hang here
});
```

questions.codeBlock:
// Regular middleware
app.use((req, res, next) => { ... });

// Error-handling middleware
app.use((err, req, res, next) => { ... });

questions.explanationMd:
Express identifies error-handling middleware by its **function signature** — it must have exactly **4 parameters**: `(err, req, res, next)`.

This is one of the few places in JavaScript where the number of declared parameters matters!

```js
// Error handler (4 params)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Something broke!' });
});
```

⚠️ If you accidentally omit a parameter, Express won't recognize it as an error handler.

